abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Nov. 10. -- Resolutions of sympathy with a man in jail for the murder of another were passed by the Methodist Episcopal Union Congregation at Diamond and Twentieth Streets to-day. abstract: BOSTON, Nov. 9. -- It cannot be said that there is any change of moment in the copper mining industry. The various companies are "keeping still and sawing wood"; in other words, operating, if at all, on a reduced scale and with economy, and awaiting the time when the metal shall appreciate in price. Sales are not reported nowadays, if any are made, and all eyes are on the future.

It is open to all amateurs, entries closing with Robert Moore, Superintendent, Tuxedo Park, on Nov. 27, and application for rooms should be made to him.

abstract: That this is an "off year" in theatricals is an indisputable fact, but the many failures are not wholly or even largely due to the financial depression. abstract: PARIS, Nov. 16. -- Arthur King Laflin of Chicago had the honor this week of being the first man ever to pay the initiation fee of the famous La Boulie Golf Club. Long ago, before golf was fashionable in Paris, it was decided that no initiation fee should be charged until the membership numbered 500. Mr. Laflin was the five hundred and first member elected. The club has become a remarkable rendezvous for cosmopolitan society.

abstract: CHICAGO, Nov. 18. -- The decision of the National Government to issue $150,000,000 in bonds and certificates met with general approval throughout the West. Bulls were more disposed to buy than for some time past, and shorts took to cover hastily as soon as the plan was announced.

abstract: BURLINGTON, N.J., Nov. 21 -- E.S. Jefferson, a well-to-do grocer, was murdered here before 11:30 o'clock to-night, one block from his home. abstract: BOSTON, Nov. 23. -- Very little of an encouraging nature is to be said about the copper mining industry.
